from sort of one stage of my career to another, or I'm going to become more senior, and, like,

00:18:24.680 --> 00:18:28.680
what should people look for if that's what they desire?

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:36.680
Yeah, so, when I wanted to, or when someone wants to, like, take more of that management

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:44.680
role, then, it depends on the company, but what could happen is you start asking for consultants,

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:48.680
or you start bringing consultants and start mentoring them to solve whatever problem it is.

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:53.680
And once they start seeing, your managers are starting seeing that you're doing very well

00:18:53.680 --> 00:18:59.680
with doing the interpersonal relationship and all that, then that can help identify that you're ready.

00:18:59.680 --> 00:19:04.680
And, of course, communication with your manager is the key. I've always been very close with my

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:10.680
managers to make sure that I've known what are my goals, what do I plan to do, what do I want to do in the future,

00:19:10.680 --> 00:19:17.680
and what can I do to demonstrate that I have that ability, or what are the things I should improve on

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:22.680
to show that I'm ready for that or will be ready for that.

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:30.680
But then the other thing is also being very, the communication ability is also key.

00:19:31.680 --> 00:19:37.680
When I was way in the beginning, I wasn't good at presentations. I wasn't good at speaking in front of a large amount of people.

00:19:37.680 --> 00:19:44.680
I was very shy, and I can go very technical really fast, and I just didn't know how to slow down

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:51.680
and make sure that, or be kind of says that not everyone understands the tech as well.

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:54.680
So I had to change the way I'm using the wording.

00:19:54.680 --> 00:20:02.680
And so once I did a lot of soft skill growth in that, so I did a lot of different classes and whatnot.

00:20:02.680 --> 00:20:09.680
And so once you start learning those skill sets, that actually helps you to move on to move on higher

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:17.680
because what I find is it's not really the beauty of that coding work and all of that that really the managers see.

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:25.680
It's your communication on how to present that and show why, and describe in words on why was this difficult challenge

00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:29.680
or what benefit does this challenge itself and this challenge give.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:33.680
And it's that that actually gets noticed. It's not, fortunately, not the work behind the scenes.

00:20:33.680 --> 00:20:37.680
So like, for example, you build a giant application that can do so many different things.

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:43.680
They don't see those tens of thousands of lines of code, or hundreds of thousands of lines of code.

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:49.680
All they see is the app itself. So then that is your key selling point is what is in the app that's useful there.

00:20:49.680 --> 00:20:58.680
What is elegant there? Because if you talk about a code, they're not going to be that interested.

00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:02.680
Very good. I'm switching over to the Slido questions.

00:21:02.680 --> 00:21:08.680
And one question is, can you talk about any challenges you faced in setting up the systems,

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:14.680
environments for data science leaders and in working with them to get what they wanted?

00:21:14.680 --> 00:21:20.680
Yes. So the biggest challenge was, at least in the beginning.

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:25.680
So a little while back when like analytics and data science was kind of new.

00:21:25.680 --> 00:21:33.680
And so you're trying to bring in platforms that no one knew how to do or install because it's new.

00:21:33.680 --> 00:21:44.680
But then, too, is a culture change of allowing people to start having access to stuff and start building products on the business side.

00:21:44.680 --> 00:21:49.680
And so that was one of the biggest challenges was just changing the culture.

00:21:49.680 --> 00:21:59.680
And then in addition to that, when it comes to the technical side, is now it's no longer having an application connect to one thing.

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:03.680
You want to have an application that can just in general connect to anything.

00:22:03.680 --> 00:22:10.680
And so that's also a little shift of how things work. So at the time I was in business,

00:22:10.680 --> 00:22:18.680
we had to come up with our own test cases to run through all the database connections or run other jobs to make sure things work.

00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:29.680
And now the only way you could bring it into the company was by doing that, because otherwise then it becomes a full IT owner owned project and all that.

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:40.680
And just it's a little different. So nowadays, I think companies are getting or IT departments are getting much more open to these analytics systems.

00:22:40.680 --> 00:22:45.680
But I think back then it was a little more challenging.

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:53.680
Yeah, I'll press a little bit. I think there might be a perception that IT is difficult to work through or work with.

00:22:53.680 --> 00:22:57.680
Curious your thoughts on that perception and what you would say.

00:22:57.680 --> 00:23:01.680
So it was a lot eye opening for me when I'm moving from business to IT.

00:23:01.680 --> 00:23:09.680
And I learned and appreciate a lot more of why it's so difficult.

00:23:10.680 --> 00:23:14.680
And there's a lot of things we don't think about when we're in the business side.

00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:18.680
I mean, we do, but how much work it actually takes that we don't think about.

00:23:18.680 --> 00:23:29.680
For example, when we say let's bring a platform into our studio, when I say bring our studio into the environment,

00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:34.680
we can just make a request like that and then hopefully one day someone will bring it in or IT will bring it in.

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:37.680
But then let's take a step back and see what IT does for that.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:42.680
Well, IT would first need to do a full review of that product.

00:23:42.680 --> 00:23:49.680
It would open up to security concerns, the data loss.

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:53.680
What are the installation tech needs to be?

00:23:53.680 --> 00:23:56.680
So meaning like do we need VMs? How big of VMs do we need?

00:23:56.680 --> 00:23:58.680
How big of a use case do people have?

00:23:58.680 --> 00:24:02.680
What about other use cases that are going to be leveraging this?

00:24:02.680 --> 00:24:09.680
For example, whatever you want to use, TensorFlow or, you know, it's a modeling software.

00:24:09.680 --> 00:24:13.680
So that's an extension to that application.

00:24:13.680 --> 00:24:17.680
What about communication? Like you have RStudio Connect.

00:24:17.680 --> 00:24:21.680
So who's going to actually monitor that?

00:24:21.680 --> 00:24:25.680
Are we going to bring it up and running and then someone else is going to oversee it?

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:28.680
What about actual support of these things to keep it up and running?

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:32.680
So if a ticket comes, like you can't access RStudio, who's going to support that?

00:24:32.680 --> 00:24:36.680
So we have to make sure it's a support team actually in line for that.

00:24:36.680 --> 00:24:39.680
What is the SLAs? I mean, what is the third level agreement?

00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:49.680
Meaning that if I'm making requests to have access to the service, well, how long should it take for that to be actually done?

00:24:49.680 --> 00:24:51.680
And then who actually is going to fulfill those?

00:24:52.680 --> 00:24:55.680
Is it the data side? Is it the security side?

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:58.680
You've got to determine all that.

00:24:58.680 --> 00:25:00.680
What about the whole architecture?

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:07.680
Like if you're a global company, well, you need to think about do I need regional setups or do I need just one giant one?

00:25:07.680 --> 00:25:09.680
What about all the databases that connect to you?

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:12.680
Consider data privacy, data localization.

00:25:12.680 --> 00:25:15.680
And what about a failover?

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:24.680
So meaning that if your whole IT center just turned off, how do you make sure everything comes back on and running?

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:26.680
They're running somewhere else.

00:25:26.680 --> 00:25:28.680
Disaster recovery.

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:30.680
All those things need to be thought about.

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:32.680
All those things need to be considered.

00:25:32.680 --> 00:25:35.680
And so the appreciation of that happens when I move over.

00:25:35.680 --> 00:25:39.680
I get these questions now all the time when I'm putting in a new system.

00:25:40.680 --> 00:25:51.680
It's like, oh, we have to think about all these different items in order to even get started with it.

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:53.680
There is an anonymous question.

00:25:53.680 --> 00:25:58.680
I'd be curious if you'd be willing to share a great example of how your team has had a big impact.

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:03.680
Also, are actuaries as fun and exciting as they say?

00:26:03.680 --> 00:26:08.680
Yeah, so I talked about doing my actuary days.

00:26:08.680 --> 00:26:16.680
So there's a couple of products we brought up, and one of them was dealing with data validation.

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:23.680
And so this is one of the first big applications that we're using Shiny to do.

00:26:23.680 --> 00:26:30.680
And the accomplishment came from the fact that this was business created, business driven.

00:26:30.680 --> 00:26:38.680
This is a very different shift from the old days where the IT side would build applications, build everything from scratch.

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:40.680
Instead, business built it.

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:43.680
And not only did we build it, but we had test cases.

00:26:43.680 --> 00:26:45.680
We used code.

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:47.680
We used databases.

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:49.680
We had staging.

00:26:49.680 --> 00:26:51.680
We had dev staging and prod.

00:26:51.680 --> 00:26:56.680
We have all those different things that a general IT team would have.

00:26:57.680 --> 00:27:03.680
We rolled that out and made it available because now it's on the web page and people can access it without needing no code.

00:27:03.680 --> 00:27:13.680
And so that was probably the biggest eye-opening for that.

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:37.680
And, yes, actuaries, we are not so ‑‑ I think that idea of actuaries being very introverted and whatnot is at least the ones I know are very outgoing and very passionate about the numbers and about the statistics and the work they do.

00:27:38.680 --> 00:27:42.680
So maybe that's a new generation actuary coming up.

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:44.680
A little more on that.

00:27:44.680 --> 00:27:50.680
There's a hybrid anonymous, not anonymous question submitted by Sam through Slido.

00:27:50.680 --> 00:27:55.680
I'm a statistician slash data scientist who has to work with many actuaries.

00:27:55.680 --> 00:27:59.680
How are data science and actuarial science different or similar?

00:28:00.680 --> 00:28:20.680
Yeah, so from my view, a data science person or data scientist should be able to jump into any domain and all they need to know is where's the data, what is the data, show me the data dictionary, what is the insight you're trying to get out of there and maybe understand the business process.

00:28:21.680 --> 00:28:23.680
An actuary kind of knows a whole domain.

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:38.680
So might be if there's an actuary slash data scientist would I think have a little edge in the sense of they understand the methodology behind it all and can give insight on how to actually build analysis around that.

00:28:38.680 --> 00:28:46.680
Without that, a data scientist might be a little bit lost unless they have to work closely with business to do that.

00:28:46.680 --> 00:28:49.680
So it's kind of like that.

00:28:49.680 --> 00:29:06.680
Either you start from scratch, don't know much, but you can learn quickly and find the right people to do it or you have someone who as an actuary slash data scientist can have enough to get started and run with it.

00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:07.680
Very good.

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:09.680
Also anonymous.

00:29:09.680 --> 00:29:12.680
What new processes have you brought to generate?

00:29:12.680 --> 00:29:14.680
How big of an impact?

00:29:14.680 --> 00:29:15.680
I guess we can append that.

00:29:15.680 --> 00:29:23.680
What impact are you hoping to make in the next one year, five years?

00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:27.680
I can't get too much into that.

00:29:27.680 --> 00:29:41.680
But I will say that understanding the power of data is what I'm targeting.

00:29:42.680 --> 00:29:44.680
I can't really divulge more than that.

00:29:44.680 --> 00:29:45.680
Understood.

00:29:45.680 --> 00:29:49.680
No problem.

00:29:49.680 --> 00:29:50.680
Let's see.

00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:57.680
If you can share, what tools does Gen Re use for catastrophe modeling?

00:29:57.680 --> 00:30:06.680
That's a little specific for me as we just provided services for usage of that tool.

00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:08.680
Gotcha.

00:30:08.680 --> 00:30:10.680
And then another anonymous question.

00:30:10.680 --> 00:30:16.680
What kinds of things worked for you in changing the culture in your organization?

00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:22.680
I think getting the right personnel in place.

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:37.680
So finding people that are passionate about data science or whatever topic it is and being expert in that and both the engineering level, like I was saying earlier, but also at the leadership level.

00:30:37.680 --> 00:30:54.680
I think that's a way to make things change because at the end of the day, people want to hear things from the experts and people who have had a lot of experience doing that, both from leadership and from actually doing the work.

00:30:54.680 --> 00:31:08.680
I had a question that I thought of, which is, as you've progressed in your career, is there any sort of discomfort around pulling away from the actual pools and in the weeds and building applications?

00:31:08.680 --> 00:31:09.680
Oh, yes.

00:31:09.680 --> 00:31:10.680
Yes.

00:31:10.680 --> 00:31:19.680
So it's like I'm trying to stop myself from jumping into a project and start running code.

00:31:19.680 --> 00:31:34.680
And it's more because I need to be, I want to be able to more mentor others to be able to do that and to the different wireframes I build or oversee or the methodologies that I've done.

00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:41.680
I have spent more time on strategy and more of those type of high-level questions and discussions.

00:31:41.680 --> 00:31:45.680
And so I would like to dig in.

00:31:45.680 --> 00:31:49.680
I still write R Markdown books internally.

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:55.680
I still write little applets or small pieces of code if something's really challenging.

00:31:56.680 --> 00:32:00.680
But, yeah, I haven't really coded, I want to say, for a couple of years now.

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:03.680
And I do mess up a little bit.

00:32:03.680 --> 00:32:07.680
And I always have my fun once in a while.

00:32:07.680 --> 00:32:09.680
I come from the old days.

00:32:09.680 --> 00:32:12.680
So base R was my background.

00:32:12.680 --> 00:32:17.680
So I can write base R very, very thoroughly.

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:24.680
So it's always fun when some of the new people will come up with a tidy verse and all that and do that.

00:32:24.680 --> 00:32:25.680
This is the way to do it.

00:32:25.680 --> 00:32:26.680
It's the only way to do it.

00:32:26.680 --> 00:32:29.680
And it's a little fun to be like, okay, you can do it this way.

00:32:29.680 --> 00:32:30.680
Let's do a little benchmarking.

00:32:30.680 --> 00:32:33.680
And I'll show you some differences you can do.

00:32:33.680 --> 00:32:45.680
So it's always fun when you have the old timer trying to show the new people there is some stock in the old knowledge.

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:56.680
So, you know, when you're sponsoring or managing people, how do you balance sort of giving direction or, like, saying, you know, this is what I would do?

00:32:56.680 --> 00:32:59.680
Or, like, hop in and actually do that?

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:05.680
Like how do you determine that line?

00:33:05.680 --> 00:33:10.680
I guess it's so blurred that I don't know.

00:33:10.680 --> 00:33:27.680
As a manager, manager of managers, my job is to make sure that the overall direction the vertical is going continues the right path.

00:33:27.680 --> 00:33:32.680
So that's basically how far I go with the management of managers.

00:33:32.680 --> 00:33:45.680
I try to make sure that we have a shared vision or shared idea of where we're going to go the next year, the next five years.

00:33:45.680 --> 00:33:48.680
So it's very much that.

00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:55.680
When it comes to the mentoring part, it really depends on what vertical we're focusing on.

00:33:55.680 --> 00:34:02.680
Because I have a lot of trust and a lot of faith in each of these verticals.

00:34:02.680 --> 00:34:10.679
And so I let them drive where they go as long as it follows that vision or follows our path.

00:34:10.679 --> 00:34:22.679
And I let them escalate things to me where things are either got a little bump in the road and need some course correction or we need additional resources or whatnot.

00:34:22.679 --> 00:34:27.679
So, yeah, this is very much of a trust thing.

00:34:27.679 --> 00:34:31.679
Thank you. There's a question from Alan in the chat.

00:34:31.679 --> 00:34:34.679
Alan, if you want to ask it.

00:34:34.679 --> 00:34:36.679
Welcome.

00:34:36.679 --> 00:34:38.679
Hi. Sure. Yeah, often.

00:34:38.679 --> 00:34:48.679
I'm curious about a little bit more detail. Matthew about your move into it and if there were things that you found to be particularly effective in streamlining.

00:34:48.679 --> 00:34:53.679
Some of those it process requirements resourcing sustainment.

00:34:53.679 --> 00:34:58.679
You know, the implementation etc. Those are familiar dilemmas for us as well.

00:34:58.679 --> 00:35:07.679
And I'm used to seeing folks I think come from it to business and then we have to realize how do we ask things, having just left that function.

00:35:07.679 --> 00:35:12.679
So I'm curious if there are specific things that you feel made that successful.

00:35:12.679 --> 00:35:22.679
And if you also had to negotiate being sort of in, in, you know, being constrained by conflicting priorities within it.

00:35:22.679 --> 00:35:28.679
And just, you know what that what helped there or what or what hindered you there.

00:35:28.679 --> 00:35:30.679
Yes.

00:35:31.679 --> 00:35:33.679
Questions.

00:35:33.679 --> 00:35:35.679
I might not remember them all.

00:35:35.679 --> 00:35:37.679
But I think.

00:35:37.679 --> 00:35:47.679
I think that I think the big thing is coming from a business side, moving on to an IT.

00:35:47.679 --> 00:36:06.679
Coming from a coding background, or like a technical background, is that I have a have a flavor of both the way to communicate or to to change the language from a technical language into a business language because I've been in business I can talk

00:36:07.679 --> 00:36:22.679
statistics helps a lot. So having someone to be able to do that translation helps with the communication with business, because if you don't have that things get lost in between.

00:36:22.679 --> 00:36:35.679
You don't want to get to a point when you're over complicating and with technical knowledge because sometimes business doesn't care about that part they care about what's actually being delivered.

00:36:35.679 --> 00:36:53.679
And then from the IT side. I also would need to be able to come up with actual technical requirements or a technical needs that I need to get from the IT side so maybe it's infrastructure maybe some security, which are technically inclined.

00:36:53.679 --> 00:37:10.679
And so I need to make sure I can also talk in that language. So it's very much of being, being someone who can do both of those communications or interpreter, as well as someone who can have the direction of where they want to go with it all, but how that being able to be interpreted

00:37:10.679 --> 00:37:16.679
at the same time is, I want to say, very beneficial.

00:37:17.679 --> 00:37:22.679
I think I've had all the hits everything but Alan, feel free.

00:37:22.679 --> 00:37:30.679
I think being able to sort of speak the kind of language in each of those domains is really important to dig in a tiny bit more like did you have to.

00:37:30.679 --> 00:37:41.679
Did you have to compete for limited it resources, and were there things that made that particularly effective.

00:37:41.679 --> 00:37:43.679
I wouldn't say compete.

00:37:43.679 --> 00:37:59.679
It's more of convincing on the priority of different projects. So, as long as there's alignment, along, along the senior management of it.

00:38:00.679 --> 00:38:11.679
These are the projects that are going on, and these are the ones that are getting prioritized and if there's a resource need there then that's kind of like where that discussion is happening.

00:38:11.679 --> 00:38:16.679
So as long as there's alignment and discussion happening then it's fine.

00:38:16.679 --> 00:38:18.679
So I wouldn't.

00:38:19.679 --> 00:38:21.679
Thank you, appreciate that.

00:38:21.679 --> 00:38:34.679
There's an anonymous question that asks, what advice would you give someone managing a data science team. And I think we can just apply it more broadly, a team for the first time.

00:38:35.679 --> 00:38:37.679
I'm having a lot of check ins in the beginning.

00:38:37.679 --> 00:38:52.679
So, so there's a lot of different approaches that I've tried a couple of them is during a stand up so meaning that having those five minutes, 10 minutes, call for the whole team figure out what all the, all the times is this lovely also have some interactive

00:38:53.679 --> 00:38:55.679
personal pieces there.

00:38:55.679 --> 00:39:07.679
But then also having those one on one to like so each of my direct reports, I have a one on one with them every, every week for an hour. And that's just to talk about random stuff.

00:39:08.679 --> 00:39:18.679
And, and it's not really for me it's never been about like asking for permission for stuff it's more of what is, what is your, what is, what are you doing with your data science team.

00:39:19.679 --> 00:39:21.679
And then we can come up with a solution together.

00:39:22.679 --> 00:39:37.679
But then also talking about actual projects and, and it's not really for me it's never been about like asking for permission for stuff it's more of what is, what is your, what is, what are you trying to solve.

00:39:37.679 --> 00:39:45.679
What is your solution. And then does this, does this make sense and let's ask the right questions and then we can come up with a solution together.

00:39:46.679 --> 00:40:00.679
So it's trying to, again, build that trust with, with each, each of your direct reports so you oversee an engineering team, you want them to try to give you what are the solutions, what are their solutions because you got to weigh it.

00:40:00.679 --> 00:40:15.679
You don't want to always like say that, oh, this is the only way. There's, there's many ways it's just this different, different approaches that might take different times and different that so that's where you kind of level it and kind of talk it through.

00:40:18.679 --> 00:40:26.679
Can I ask what the structure of these check ins are you said, random topics but is it is it truly agenda list.

00:40:26.679 --> 00:40:33.679
Oh yeah, no I have a series already set up so all I can all my reports are once a week.

00:40:33.679 --> 00:40:46.679
I have overall management meetings, and I set up once a month and so yeah, I just make sure that on the calendar right so that I'm not going to worry about making those out to the back.

00:40:46.679 --> 00:40:49.679
So, six to

